                'content' => '<p>Jackfruit is one of the most fascinating tropical fruits in the world. Known for its massive size, sweet flavor, and versatility in cooking, jackfruit has become increasingly popular among food lovers, vegetarians, and health-conscious individuals. Native to South and Southeast Asia, this fruit is packed with nutrients and unique characteristics that make it stand out from other fruits. Here are 30 interesting facts about jackfruit.</p><p><br></p><ol><li>Jackfruit is the largest tree-borne fruit in the world and can weigh up to 100 pounds.</li><li>The fruit can grow up to 3 feet long and 20 inches wide.</li><li>Jackfruit originated in South and Southeast Asia.</li><li>The scientific name of jackfruit is <em>Artocarpus heterophyllus</em>.</li><li>Jackfruit belongs to the same plant family as figs and mulberries.</li><li>A mature jackfruit tree can produce up to 200 fruits each year.</li><li>The outer skin of jackfruit is green and spiky.</li><li>Ripe jackfruit has a sweet flavor often compared to banana, mango, and pineapple.</li><li>Unripe jackfruit has a meat-like texture, making it popular in vegan dishes.</li><li>Many people use young jackfruit as a substitute for pulled pork.</li><li>Jackfruit is rich in vitamin C, which helps support the immune system.</li><li>It also contains vitamin A, which supports eye health.</li><li>Jackfruit is high in dietary fiber, which helps digestion.</li><li>The fruit contains potassium, which may help regulate blood pressure.</li><li>Jackfruit contains antioxidants that help protect the body from free radicals.</li><li>Both ripe and unripe jackfruit are edible.</li><li>Jackfruit seeds can also be eaten after boiling or roasting.</li><li>The seeds contain protein, iron, and potassium.</li><li>In Bangladesh, jackfruit is considered the national fruit.</li><li>In the Philippines, jackfruit is commonly called "langka."</li><li>Jackfruit is commonly used in Filipino desserts like halo-halo.</li><li>The 